		<title>5 Myths about Women in Business (Debunked)</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/07/05/women-in-business</link>
					<comments>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/07/05/women-in-business#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jessica Deluca]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 05 Jul 2018 05:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Diversity & Inclusion]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/07/05/women-in-business/</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>The Megaphone of Mainstreet's SCORE 2018 report on women-owned businesses provides us with the data to debunk some vastly outdated myths surrounding women's role as entrepreneurs.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/07/05/women-in-business">5 Myths about Women in Business (Debunked)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p dir="ltr">Unfortunately, a lot of common misconceptions surrounding women‚Äôs place (and capacity for success) in business still exist today.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Luckily for us, when it comes to myths, common misconceptions, stereotypes, you name it,¬†<a href="https://www.score.org/resource/megaphone-main-street-women-entrepreneurs">SCORE‚Äôs spring 2018 ‚ÄúThe Megaphone of Main Street‚Äù</a> data report on women-owned businesses is here to set the record straight.</p>
<p dir="ltr">After checking the report out, we decided to dive deep into the points we hear most frequently, the ones most of us have been conditioned to accept as fact, and provide you with data and real-life examples to rewrite the narrative.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Here‚Äôs the short list:</p>
<ul>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Men are more likely to start their own business</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Women-owned businesses are mostly ‚Äúlifestyle‚Äù businesses</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Men-owned businesses produce more revenue</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Women-owned and men-owned businesses face the same level of difficulty in acquiring financing</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Men-owned businesses feel more confident in the success of their business</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p dir="ltr">With that, let‚Äôs kick these myths to the curb and recognize the tools and traits <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/12/15/controversial-answers-to-common-startup-questions-dharmesh-shah">successful entrepreneurs</a> actually possess.</p>
<p dir="ltr">(Hint: you won‚Äôt find gender on the list.)</p>
<h2 dir="ltr">MYTH: Entrepreneurs are virtually all men, because men are more likely to start their own business</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Nope! According to the Megaphone of Main Street, women are more likely than men to start a business, with 47% of women vs 44% of men poled answering yes to starting a business in the last year. And this number‚Äôs on the rise, increasing by 45% in the last 10 years.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Let‚Äôs take look at how this translates to real life. Here‚Äôs a (very) short list of companies you might‚Äôve heard of with some badass women at the helm:</p>
<ul>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">IBM, Ginni Rometty</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">PepsiCo, Indra Nooyi</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Oracle, Safra Catz</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">General Motors, Mary Barra</p>
</li>
<li dir="ltr">
<p dir="ltr">Lockheed Martin, Marillyn Hewson</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p dir="ltr">Women make up 38% of the 28 million <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2013/07/15/adwords-small-business-strategy-guide">small businesses</a> operating within the United States, and employ nearly 9 million people, all the while generating $1.6 trillion in revenues. So, mark this one as debunked. Not only are women making up more than a third of small businesses, they‚Äôve proven to be even more likely to start their own in the first place.</p>
<h2 dir="ltr">MYTH: Women-owned businesses are mostly ‚Äúlifestyle‚Äù businesses</h2>
<p dir="ltr">No, not at all.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Lifestyle businesses are businesses run for the purpose of sustaining a certain level of income and no more, with little focus on growth or revenue success. Lifestyle businesses are great and all, but it would seem as though the 62% of women entrepreneurs that depend on their business as their primary source of income would disagree with this one.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Women are also more likely than men to start businesses in the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/03/10/healthcare-marketing">healthcare</a> and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/08/04/higher-education-marketing">education industries</a>, and 19% of women-owned businesses operate in the service industry, compared to the 15% of men-owned businesses that do.</p>
<p dir="ltr">If you don‚Äôt live under a rock, you‚Äôve most likely heard of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/03/24/best-instagram-marketing-campaigns">Orangetheory</a>, known for its high-intensity workouts crafted with a mix of cardio, endurance, and strength training. Its CEO, Ellen Latham, founded the business in 2010 and topped 2017 as Forbes‚Äô fastest growing women-owned business with $451 million in sales and 700 franchises nationwide.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Orangetheory‚Äôs certainly not the only example, but I could honestly go on forever. We‚Äôll save my time and yours with this infographic that shows the percentage breakdown of women-owned businesses in some major industries.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="518d78bd-1420-4e6c-bd81-39572493a43d" data-langcode="en">
<article>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/women-owned-businesses-industry-breakdown.png" alt="women-owned-businesses-industry-breakdown" width="585" height="349" /></div>
</article>
</div>
<p dir="ltr">Let‚Äôs go ahead and correct that to, ‚Äúwomen-owned businesses operate in whatever industry they damn well please.‚Äù</p>
<h2 dir="ltr">MYTH: Men-owned businesses produce more revenue</h2>
<p dir="ltr">15.5% of both men-owned and women-owned businesses predicted static revenues in 2018, and 9.5% of men-owned predict a decrease in revenue, vs the 9% prediction from women-owned.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Here‚Äôs another handy infographic focusing on the incredible impact women-owned businesses have had on the economy. With an annual revenue of $1.3 trillion, it‚Äôs safe to say women-owned businesses aren‚Äôt just surviving when it comes to revenue production, but they‚Äôre cashing in, big time.</p>
<div class="embedded-entity align-center" data-embed-button="images" data-entity-embed-display="view_mode:media.simple_image" data-entity-type="media" data-entity-uuid="4d719e90-e4c0-4b54-a0ad-8542d6f1ec41" data-langcode="en">
